@section Usage
@cindex Usage
@cindex Programmer
@cindex Developer

The usage of a Triton GUI should be pretty clear.  All windows have two
additional keyboard shortcuts (if not explicitly disabled by the
application):

@itemize @bullet
@item
'Esc' will simulate the 'close window' gadget.
@item
'Del' will simulate the 'resize window' gadget.
@end itemize

Furthermore, various objects react on some standard keyboard shortcuts:

@itemize @bullet
@item
In palette, slider, scroller and
similar gadgets with an up/down facility you can use the shifted shortcut
to decrease the value.
@item
Listviews can be controlled with either the cursor keys (@code{Shift}ed
and @code{Alt}ernate shortcuts are also available) or the numeric
keypad (including the numeric arrow keys, @code{Home}, @code{End},
@code{PgUp} and @code{PgDn}). The programmer may choose to disable
these shortcuts, mainly in order to make the primary listview accessable
via the cursor keys and the secondary listview via the numeric keypad.
@item
Within string gadgets, @code{Tab} and @code{Shift Tab} will activate the
previous/next string gadget as usual. You can access all keyboard shortcuts
by pressing them together with the right Amiga key (@code{RAmiga}). If no
such shortcut exists, Triton will instead try to interpret the key you pressed
as a menu shortcut. You may use the cursor up and down keys normally from
within string gadgets to control a listview.
@item
You can cancel a button which has been pressed down with a keyboard shortcut
by pressing down either @code{Shift} key before releasing the shortcut.
This is similar to releasing the mouse button outside the borders of a button.
@end itemize

For information on how to use Triton as a programmer for developing Triton
applications, see the developer documentation which is included in the
Triton developer archive in the directory @file{Developer}.

